olutions at the Cold War's End: A Brief History with Documents'' (2009) \n* Sebestyen, Victor. ''Revolution 1989: The Fall of the Soviet Empire'' (2010) [https://www.amazon.com/Revolution-1989-Fall-Soviet-Empire/dp/0307387925/ excerpt]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.goethe.de/kue/the/prj/atf/enindex.htm After the fall \u2013 Europe after 1989]\n* [http://www.thenation.com/doc/20091116/kvh_cohen?rel=emailNation Mikhail Gorbachev on 1989] \u2013 2009 interview by ''[[The Nation]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091016014732/http://www.germany.info/Vertretung/usa/en/10__Press__Facts/03__Infocus/04__Without__Walls/__Main__S.html Freedom Without Walls: German Missions in the United States] Looking Back at the Fall of the Berlin Wall \u2013 official homepage in English\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1989}}\n[[Category:1989| ]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: East-West \u2192 east\u2013west, middle distance \u2192 middle-distance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989"}
{"title_page": "2020 Madhya Pradesh political crisis", "text_new": "{{short description|Political crisis in Indian state of Madhya Pradesh}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = 2020 Madhya Pradesh political crisis\n|image ={{Photomontage\n |photo1a= Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia delivering a talk on \u201cIndian Energy Security in the context of the Power Sector\u201d.(cropped).jpg\n |photo1b= Kamal Nath 2012.jpg\n |photo1c= Shivraj Sing 001.jpg\n| position = center\n| size = 300\n| color = #F5F5F5\n| border = 6\n| color_border = black\n| spacing = 3\n| foot_montage =  \n |text= {{center|[[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] (left), [[Kamal Nath]] (centre), [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] (right)}}\n}}\n| image_size               = 200px\n| image_upright            =\n| image_alt                =\n| caption                  =\n| native_name              =\n| native_name_lang         =\n| english_name             =\n| time                     =\n| duration                 =\n| date                     = 5\u201320 March 2020\n| venue                    =\n| location                 = [[Madhya Pradesh]], India \n| coordinates              =\n| also_known_as            = 2020 Madhya Pradesh government formation \n| type                     = [[Parliamentary system|Parliamentary crisis and government formation]]\n| theme                    =\n| cause                    = Resignation of [[Indian National Congress]] MLAs\n| participants             = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP)<br>[[Indian National Congress]] (INC)<br> [[Independent Politician|Other political parties and Independents]]\n| outcome                  = Fall of the [[Kamal Nath ministry|Kamal Nath government]] and Formation of [[National Democratic Alliance]] government. \n}}\nOn 10 March 2020, when [[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] resigned from [[Indian National Congress]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/jyotiraditya-scindia-resigns-from-congress/articleshow/74561583.cms|title=Jyotiraditya Scindia resigns from Congress, more than 20 party MLAs quit|date=2020-03-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> his supporter 22 [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLAs]] also resigned. They sent their resignations by email to the Speaker of [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]], [[N. P. Prajapati|Narmada Prasad Prajapati]] and Governor [[Lalji Tandon]] from the hotel of [[Bengaluru]].\n\n==Background==\nAfter the 2018 Assembly elections in Madhya Pradesh,no party got majority although [[Indian National Congress]] was the single largest party in the assembly. [[Indian National Congress]] formed the government with the help of one [[Bahujan Samaj Party|BSP]] MLA and one [[Samajwadi Party|SP]] MLA and other independent MLAs.\n\n[[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] had asked [[Rahul Gandhi]], then Congress President to make him either Chief Minister, Deputy Chief Minister or the President of the [[Madhya Pradesh Congress Committee]], but he denied and made [[Kamal Nath]] as Chief Minister. \n==Crisis==\nOn 10 March 2020, Scindia suddenly went to meet [[Narendra Modi]], Prime Minister of India and [[Amit Shah]], Home Minister of India. After meeting them, at around 11:30 am, he resigned from the [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] party, saying that he felt very guilty while working for Congress.<ref>Jyotiraditya M. Scindia (@JM_Scindia) Tweeted:\nhttps://twitter.com/JM_Scindia/status/1237266942961967104?s=20</ref>\n\nNext day, at around 3:00 pm, he joined [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in the presence of [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]], National President of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. \n\nAfter joining the party, he slammed [[Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh]], [[Kamal Nath]] and other [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] leaders for not giving the importance in the party. Throughout his [[press conference]], he didn't mention the names of the [[Nehru-Gandhi Family]]. After joining the party, he was given the ticket of [[Rajya Sabha]] from Madhya Pradesh by [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]]. \n\nBoth the parties have reached Supreme Court to ask for a floor test in Madhya Pradesh and the Supreme Court said that the floor test in [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] should be done on 20 March 2020 by 5:00 pm. On 20 March 2020, at around 12:00 pm, during a press conference, Chief Minister [[Kamal Nath]] resigned as CM. After that, on 23 March 2020, [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] took oath as CM.\n\n===List of Members who Resigned===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! S.No\n! Constituency\n! Member\n! colspan=2| Party\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|1. \n|[[Surkhi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Surkhi]]\n|'''[[Govind Singh Rajput]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n| rowspan=\"22\" width=\"4px\" style=\"background-color: {{Indian National Congress/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=\"22\"|[[Indian National Congress]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|2. \n|[[Dabra (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Dabra]]\n|'''[[Imarti Devi]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|3. \n|[[Sanwer (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sanwer]]\n|'''[[Tulsi Silawat|Tulsi Ram Silawat]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|4. \n|[[Bamori (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bamori]]\n|'''[[Mahendra Singh Sisodia]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|5. \n|[[Sanchi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sanchi]]\n|'''[[Prabhuram Choudhary]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|6.\n|[[Gwalior (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gwalior]]\n|'''[[Pradhumn Singh Tomar]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|7.\n|[[Ashok Nagar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Ashok Nagar]]\n|[[Jaipal Singh Jajji]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|8.\n|[[Karera (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Karera]]\n|[[Jasvant Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|9.\n|[[Suwasra (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Suwasra]]\n|[[Hardeep Singh Dang]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|10.\n|[[Gohad (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gohad]]\n|[[Ranvir Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|11.\n|[[Gwalior East (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gwalior East]]\n|[[Munnalal Goyal]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|12. \n|[[Anuppur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Anuppur]]\n|[[Bisahu Lal Singh]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|13.\n|[[Morena (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Morena]]\n|[[Raghuraj Singh Kansana]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|14.\n|[[Badnawar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Badnawar]]\n|[[Rajvardhan Singh Dattigaon]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|15.\n|[[Mehgaon (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mehgaon]]\n|[[OPS Bhadoria]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|16.\n|[[Ambah (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Ambah]]\n|[[Kamalesh Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|17. \n|[[Mungaoli (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mungaoli]]\n|[[Brajendra Yadav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|18. \n|[[Pohari (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Pohari]]\n|[[Suresh Rathkheda Dhakad]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|19. \n|[[Bhander (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bhander]]\n|[[Raksha Santram Saroniya]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|20.\n|[[Dimani (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Dimani]]\n|[[Girraj Dandotiya]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|21.\n|[[Sumawali (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sumawali]]\n|[[Aidal Singh Kansana]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|22.\n|[[Hatpipliya (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Hatpipliya]]\n|[[Manoj Choudhary]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|}\n\n===Formation of New Government===\nA new [[Government of Madhya Pradesh|government]] is supposed to be formed by [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].\n\nOn 21 March 2020, in [[Delhi]], all the 22 rebel [[Indian National Congress|Congress MLAs]] joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], in presence of [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Bharatiya Janata Party's]] national president [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]]. [[Jyotiraditya Scindia]], [[Dharmendra Pradhan]], [[Narottam Mishra]] and many of the senior [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP leaders]] were also present.<ref>{{cite news |title =22 rebel Cong MLAs, whose resignation led to fall of Kamal Nath govt, join BJP|url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/22-rebel-cong-mlas-whose-resignation-led-to-fall-of-kamal-nath-govt-join-bjp-11584797981690.html|publisher=Live Mint}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2019 Karnataka political crisis]]\n* [[2019 Maharashtra political crisis]]\n\n[[Category:2020 in Indian politics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:2020s in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political crisis in Indian state of Madhya Pradesh}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = 2020 Madhya Pradesh political crisis\n|image ={{Photomontage\n |photo1a= Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia delivering a talk on \u201cIndian Energy Security in the context of the Power Sector\u201d.(cropped).jpg\n |photo1b= Kamal Nath 2012.jpg\n |photo1c= Shivraj Sing 001.jpg\n| position = center\n| size = 300\n| color = #F5F5F5\n| border = 6\n| color_border = black\n| spacing = 3\n| foot_montage =  \n |text= {{center|[[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] (left), [[Kamal Nath]] (centre), [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] (right)}}\n}}\n| image_size               = 200px\n| image_upright            =\n| image_alt                =\n| caption                  =\n| native_name              =\n| native_name_lang         =\n| english_name             =\n| time                     =\n| duration                 =\n| date                     = 5\u201320 March 2020\n| venue                    =\n| location                 = [[Madhya Pradesh]], India \n| coordinates              =\n| also_known_as            = 2020 Madhya Pradesh government formation \n| type                     = [[Parliamentary system|Parliamentary crisis and government formation]]\n| theme                    =\n| cause                    = Resignation of [[Indian National Congress]] MLAs\n| participants             = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP)<br>[[Indian National Congress]] (INC)<br> [[Independent Politician|Other political parties and Independents]]\n| outcome                  = Fall of the [[Kamal Nath ministry|Kamal Nath government]] and Formation of [[National Democratic Alliance]] government. \n}}\nOn 10 March 2020, when [[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] resigned from [[Indian National Congress]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/jyotiraditya-scindia-resigns-from-congress/articleshow/74561583.cms|title=Jyotiraditya Scindia resigns from Congress, more than 20 party MLAs quit|date=2020-03-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> his supporter 22 [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLAs]] also resigned. They sent their resignations by email to the Speaker of [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]], [[N. P. Prajapati|Narmada Prasad Prajapati]] and Governor [[Lalji Tandon]] from the hotel of [[Bengaluru]].\n\n==Background==\nAfter the 2018 Assembly elections in Madhya Pradesh,no party got majority although [[Indian National Congress]] was the single largest party in the assembly. [[Indian National Congress]] formed the government with the help of one [[Bahujan Samaj Party|BSP]] MLA and one [[Samajwadi Party|SP]] MLA and other independent MLAs.\n\n[[Jyotiraditya Scindia]] had asked [[Rahul Gandhi]], then Congress President to make him either Chief Minister, Deputy Chief Minister or the President of the [[Madhya Pradesh Congress Committee]], but he denied and made [[Kamal Nath]] as Chief Minister. \n==Crisis==\nOn 10 March 2020, Scindia suddenly went to meet [[Narendra Modi]], Prime Minister of India and [[Amit Shah]], Home Minister of India. After meeting them, at around 11:30 am, he resigned from the [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] party, saying that he felt very guilty while working for Congress.<ref>Jyotiraditya M. Scindia (@JM_Scindia) Tweeted:\nhttps://twitter.com/JM_Scindia/status/1237266942961967104?s=20</ref>\n\nNext day, at around 3:00 pm, he joined [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in the presence of [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]], National President of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. \n\nAfter joining the party, he slammed [[Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh]], [[Kamal Nath]] and other [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] leaders for not giving the importance in the party. Throughout his [[press conference]], he didn't mention the names of the [[Nehru-Gandhi Family]]. After joining the party, he was given the ticket of [[Rajya Sabha]] from Madhya Pradesh by [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]]. \n\nBoth the parties have reached Supreme Court to ask for a floor test in Madhya Pradesh and the Supreme Court said that the floor test in [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] should be done on 20 March 2020 by 5:00 pm. On 20 March 2020, at around 12:00 pm, during a press conference, Chief Minister [[Kamal Nath]] resigned as CM. After that, on 23 March 2020, [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] took oath as CM.\n\n===List of Members who Resigned===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! S.No\n! Constituency\n! Member\n! colspan=2| Party\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|1. \n|[[Surkhi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Surkhi]]\n|'''[[Govind Singh Rajput]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n| rowspan=\"22\" width=\"4px\" style=\"background-color: {{Indian National Congress/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=\"22\"|[[Indian National Congress]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|2. \n|[[Dabra (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Dabra]]\n|'''[[Imarti Devi]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|3. \n|[[Sanwer (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sanwer]]\n|'''[[Tulsi Silawat|Tulsi Ram Silawat]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|4. \n|[[Bamori (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bamori]]\n|'''[[Mahendra Singh Sisodia]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|5. \n|[[Sanchi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sanchi]]\n|'''[[Prabhuram Choudhary]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|6.\n|[[Gwalior (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gwalior]]\n|'''[[Pradhumn Singh Tomar]]'''<br>[[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister]] \n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|7.\n|[[Ashok Nagar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Ashok Nagar]]\n|[[Jaipal Singh Jajji]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|8.\n|[[Karera (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Karera]]\n|[[Jasvant Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|9.\n|[[Suwasra (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Suwasra]]\n|[[Hardeep Singh Dang]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|10.\n|[[Gohad (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gohad]]\n|[[Ranvir Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|11.\n|[[Gwalior East (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Gwalior East]]\n|[[Munnalal Goyal]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|12. \n|[[Anuppur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Anuppur]]\n|[[Bisahu Lal Singh]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|13.\n|[[Morena (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Morena]]\n|[[Raghuraj Singh Kansana]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|14.\n|[[Badnawar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Badnawar]]\n|[[Rajvardhan Singh Dattigaon]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|15.\n|[[Mehgaon (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mehgaon]]\n|[[OPS Bhadoria]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|16.\n|[[Ambah (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Ambah]]\n|[[Kamalesh Jatav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|17. \n|[[Mungaoli (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mungaoli]]\n|[[Brajendra Yadav]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|18. \n|[[Pohari (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Pohari]]\n|[[Suresh Rathkheda Dhakad]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|19. \n|[[Bhander (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bhander]]\n|[[Raksha Santram Saroniya]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|20.\n|[[Dimani (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Dimani]]\n|[[Girraj Dandotiya]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|21.\n|[[Sumawali (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sumawali]]\n|[[Aidal Singh Kansana]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|22.\n|[[Hatpipliya (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Hatpipliya]]\n|[[Manoj Choudhary]]\n|-style=\"text-align:center; height:30px;\"\n|}\n\n===Formation of New Government===\nA new [[Government of Madhya Pradesh|government]] is supposed to be formed by [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]] of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].\n\nOn 21 March 2020, in [[Delhi]], all the 22 rebel [[Indian National Congress|Congress MLAs]] joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], in presence of [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Bharatiya Janata Party's]] national president [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]]. [[Jyotiraditya Scindia]], [[Dharmendra Pradhan]], [[Narottam Mishra]] and many of the senior [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP leaders]] were also present.<ref>{{cite news |title =22 rebel Cong MLAs, whose resignation led to fall of Kamal Nath govt, join BJP|url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/22-rebel-cong-mlas-whose-resignation-led-to-fall-of-kamal-nath-govt-join-bjp-11584797981690.html|publisher=Live Mint}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n\n[[Category:2020 in Indian politics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:2020s in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Docentation", "label": "safe", "comment": "added karnataka and maharashtra 