[[playoff format|series]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Trevor Gleeson]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Damian Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Casey Prather]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2017\u201318 NBL season|2017\u201318]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[National Basketball League (Australia)|NBL]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3rd\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.571 \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Lost in Semi-Finals to [[Adelaide 36ers]], 2\u20130 ([[playoff format|series]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Trevor Gleeson]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Damian Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bryce Cotton]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2018\u201319 NBL season|2018\u201319]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[National Basketball League (Australia)|NBL]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"bgcolor=gold|1st \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.643 \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"bgcolor=gold|'''Champions''' in Final against [[Melbourne United]], 3\u20131 ([[playoff format|series]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Trevor Gleeson]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Damian Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bryce Cotton]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2019\u201320 NBL season|2019\u201320]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[National Basketball League (Australia)|NBL]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|19|9}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"bgcolor=gold|'''Champions''' in Final against [[Sydney Kings]], 2\u20131 ([[playoff format|series]])\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Trevor Gleeson]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Damian Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bryce Cotton]]\n|}\n\nSource: [http://www.wildcats.com.au/pages/year-by-year Perth Wildcats Year by Year]\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:2016-17 NBL championship trophy.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The 2016/17 championship trophy]]\nAfter three years of finals action that included a losing grand final series in 1987, the team won back-to-back titles in 1990 and 1991 behind the likes of [[Ricky Grace]], [[James Crawford (basketball)|James Crawford]] and [[Mike Ellis (basketball)|Mike Ellis]], and coaches [[Cal Bruton]] and [[Murray Arnold]]. It took four more years for the team's third NBL title in 1995, with coach [[Adrian Hurley]] and captain [[Andrew Vlahov]] leading the way. Five more years elapsed before the next championship came in the 1999/2000 season. Behind coach [[Alan Black (basketball)|Alan Black]] and centre [[Paul Rogers (basketball)|Paul Rogers]], and veterans Vlahov, Grace and [[Scott Fisher (basketball)|Scott Fisher]] still around, the Wildcats won their fourth title.\n\nA large championship drought occurred between 2000/01 and 2008/09, but the Wildcats still made the finals each season. Then in 2009/10, the Wildcats became the undisputed greatest NBL franchise with a fifth championship. Coach Rob Beveridge and import [[Kevin Lisch]] were instrumental to the team's success that season, as was [[Shawn Redhage]] and [[Damian Martin]].\n\nTheir sixth championship came in 2013/14 thanks to coach [[Trevor Gleeson]] and imports [[Jermaine Beal]] and [[James Ennis (basketball)|James Ennis]]. In 2014/15, the Wildcats qualified for the finals for a 29th straight year, a streak not matched by any Australian or American professional sports team other than the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[Boston Bruins]]. Their seventh championship came the next season in 2015/16, as coach Gleeson became the first Wildcats coach to win multiple championships. With their eighth title coming in 2016/17, the Wildcats won back-to-back championships for the first time since 1990/1991, while Gleeson became the first coach to guide the Wildcats to consecutive championships. In 2017, four-time championship-winning trio Damian Martin, Shawn Redhage and [[Jesse Wagstaff]] equaled Ricky Grace's franchise record of winning four championships. In 2019, Martin and Wagstaff became the only players in NBL history to win five championships at the one club.<ref name=\"ninth1\" /><ref name=\"ninth2\" /> Martin and Wagstaff picked up their sixth championship rings in 2020, joining [[C. J. Bruton]] and [[David Stiff (basketball)|David Stiff]] as the NBL's only six-time champions and the only players to be able to do that at one club. Additionally, Gleeson attained his fifth NBL championship, making him the second-most successful coach in league history behind six-time winner [[Brian Goorjian]].<ref name=\"champions2020\" />\n\n===Finals appearance record===\nThe Perth Wildcats' run of 34 straight NBL finals appearances since 1987 is unmatched in major Australian professional sports. The most consecutive finals reached in [[Australian Football League|VFL/AFL]] football is 14 by the [[Hawthorn Football Club]] between 1982 and 1994, while the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]'s [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] made 23 consecutive finals appearances between 1951 and 1973.\n\nIt is matched in the [[major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major North American sports]] only by the [[Edmonton Eskimos]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], which qualified for the playoffs for 34 consecutive years between 1972 and 2005. In [[sports in the United States|American sport]], the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] (as the Syracuse Nationals) made the [[NBA playoffs]] 22 straight seasons between 1949/50 and 1970/71, marking the best streak in the world's premier basketball league. In [[Major League Baseball]], the best streak is held by the [[Atlanta Braves]], who made 14 straight playoff appearances between 1992 and 2005. The only major professional team in the United States that had a record close to the Wildcats' 34 was the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[Boston Bruins]], who made 29 consecutive playoff appearances between 1967/68 and 1995/96.<ref name=equalB>{{cite web | url=http://www.wildcats.com.au/article/id/1g88mkt2vkntg1xkdv6vr35q25 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223111357/http://www.wildcats.com.au/article/id/1g88mkt2vkntg1xkdv6vr35q25 | url-status=dead | archive-date=23 February 2015 | title=Perth Wildcats equal world record | work=Wildcats.com.au | date=23 February 2015 | accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Wildcats' 34 still trails Israeli professional basketball club [[Maccabi Tel Aviv B.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]]'s [[world record]] of 38 straight post-season appearances, with their 38th appearance coming in 2018/19<!--The Israeli League first had playoffs in 1981/82, and Maccabi Tel Aviv have made the playoffs every season.-->.<ref name=\"thirty-straight\"/>\n\n==Arena history==\n* [[Perry Lakes Basketball Stadium]] (1982\u20131986)\n* [[HBF Stadium|Perth Superdrome / Challenge Stadium]] (1987\u20131989, 2002\u20132012)\n* [[Perth Entertainment Centre]] (1990\u20132002)\n* [[Crown Perth#Burswood Dome (demolished)|Burswood Dome]] (1994; 2004)\n* [[Perth Arena|RAC Arena]] (2012\u2013present)\n\n==Players==\n:See also: [http://www.wildcats.com.au/history/complete-player-list/ Perth Wildcats Complete Player List]\n\n===Current roster===\n<section begin=roster />{{Basketball roster nationality note}}\n{{Basketball roster header|type=NBL|age=n\n| team=Perth Wildcats}}\n<!-- list of players -->\n{{player3 | pos = F | num = 3 | nat = AUS | first = Nick | last = Kay | m = 2.06 | kgs = 106 }}\n{{player3 | pos = G | num = 8 | nat = AUS | first = Mitch | last = Norton | m = 1.86 | kgs = 91 }}\n{{player3 | pos = G/F | num = 9 | nat = AUS | first = Wani | last = Swaka Lo Buluk | m = 1.94 | kgs = 87 }}\n{{player3