{"title_page": "Manjula Padmanabhan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n'''Manjula Padmanabhan''' (born 1953) is a playwright, journalist, comic strip artist, and children's book author.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Delhi to a diplomat family in 1953, she went to boarding school in her teenage years. After college,  her determination to make her own way in life led to works in publishing and media-related fields.\n\n==Career & Works==\nShe won the Greek Onassis Award for her play ''[[The Harvest (1997)|Harvest]]''. An award-winning film ''[[Deham]]'' was made by [[Govind Nihalani]] based on the play.\n\nShe has written one more powerful play, ''Lights Out!'' (1984), ''Hidden Fires'' is a series of monologues. ''The Artist's Model'' (1995) and ''Sextet'' are her other works.(1996).<ref name=\"hindi1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/01/03/stories/2009010350250200.htm|title=Is it the great escape?|last=Matthan|first=Ayesha|date=2009-01-03|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref>\n\nShe has also authored a collection of short stories, called ''Kleptomania''. Her most recent book, published in 2008, is ''Escape''.<ref name=\"hindi1\" />\n \nApart from writing newspaper columns she created comic strips. She created Suki, an Indian comic character, which was serialized as a strip in the ''[[Sunday Observer]]''.<ref name=\"hindi2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2005/08/28/stories/2005082800140500.htm|title=Antics of Suki|last=Moddie|first=Mandira|date=2005-08-28|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref> Before 1997 (the year her play ''Harvest'' was staged) she was better known as cartoonist and had a daily cartoon strip in ''[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]]'' newspaper.\n\n===As playwright===\n*1984 - \"Lights Out\"\n* 2003. ''Harvest''. London: Aurora Metro Books (website) [https://www.aurorametro.com/product/harvest/]\n\n===As Author and Illustrator===\n* 2013. ''Three Virgins and Other Stories'' New Delhi, India: Zubaan Books.\n*2015. ''Island of Lost Girls.'' Hachette.\n* 2011. ''I am different! Can you find me?'' Watertown, Mass: Charlesbridge Pub.\n*2008. ''Escape''. Hachette.\n* 2005. ''Unprincess!'' New Delhi: Puffin Books.\n* 1986. ''A Visit to the City Market'' New Delhi: National Book Trust\n* 2003. ''Mouse Attack''\n\n===As Illustrator===\n* Baig, Tara Ali, and Manjula Padmanabhan. 1979. ''Indrani and the enchanted jungle.'' New Delhi: Thomson Press (India) Ltd.\n* Maithily Jagannathan and Manjula Padmanabhan. 1984. ''Droopy dragon''. New Delhi: Thomson Press.\n\n===Comic Strips===\n* 2005. ''Double talk''. New Delhi: Penguin Books.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Padmanabhan, Manjula}}\n[[Category:Indian women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian comics writers]]\n[[Category:Indian cartoonists]]\n[[Category:Indian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Indian women illustrators]]\n[[Category:Indian women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Indian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Indian children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian female comics artists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n\n\n{{India-writer-stub}}\n{{comic-strip-creator-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n'''Manjula Padmanabhan''' (born 1953) is a playwright, journalist, comic strip artist, and children's book author.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Delhi to a diplomat family in 1953, she went to boarding school in her teenage years. After college,  her determination to make her own way in life led to works in publishing and media-related fields.\n\n==Career & Works==\nShe won the Greek Onassis Award for her play ''[[The Harvest (1997)|Harvest]]''. An award-winning film ''[[Deham]]'' was made by [[Govind Nihalani]] based on the play.\n\nShe has written one more powerful play, ''Lights Out!'' (1984), ''Hidden Fires'' is a series of monologues. ''The Artist's Model'' (1995) and ''Sextet'' are her other works.(1996).<ref name=\"hindi1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/01/03/stories/2009010350250200.htm|title=Is it the great escape?|last=Matthan|first=Ayesha|date=2009-01-03|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref>\n\nShe has also authored a collection of short stories, called ''Kleptomania''. Her most recent book, published in 2008, is ''Escape''.<ref name=\"hindi1\" />\n \nApart from writing newspaper columns she created comic strips. She created Suki, an Indian comic character, which was serialized as a strip in the ''[[Sunday Observer]]''.<ref name=\"hindi2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2005/08/28/stories/2005082800140500.htm|title=Antics of Suki|last=Moddie|first=Mandira|date=2005-08-28|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref> Before 1997 (the year her play ''Harvest'' was staged) she was better known as cartoonist and had a daily cartoon strip in ''[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]]'' newspaper.\n\n===As playwright===\n*1984 - \"Lights Out\"\n* 2003. ''Harvest''. London: Aurora Metro Press.\n\n===As Author and Illustrator===\n* 2013. ''Three Virgins and Other Stories'' New Delhi, India: Zubaan Books.\n*2015. ''Island of Lost Girls.'' Hachette.\n* 2011. ''I am different! Can you find me?'' Watertown, Mass: Charlesbridge Pub.\n*2008. ''Escape''. Hachette.\n* 2005. ''Unprincess!'' New Delhi: Puffin Books.\n* 1986. ''A Visit to the City Market'' New Delhi: National Book Trust\n* 2003. ''Mouse Attack''\n\n===As Illustrator===\n* Baig, Tara Ali, and Manjula Padmanabhan. 1979. ''Indrani and the enchanted jungle.'' New Delhi: Thomson Press (India) Ltd.\n* Maithily Jagannathan and Manjula Padmanabhan. 1984. ''Droopy dragon''. New Delhi: Thomson Press.\n\n===Comic Strips===\n* 2005. ''Double talk''. New Delhi: Penguin Books.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Padmanabhan, Manjula}}\n[[Category:Indian women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian comics writers]]\n[[Category:Indian cartoonists]]\n[[Category:Indian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Indian women illustrators]]\n[[Category:Indian women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Indian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Indian children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian female comics artists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n\n\n{{India-writer-stub}}\n{{comic-strip-creator-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aurora Metro Books", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAs playwright", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manjula_Padmanabhan"}
{"title_page": "United States Futsal Federation", "text_new": "{{Infobox football association\n| Logo = \n| Badge_size = 180px\n| Founded = \n| FIFA affiliation =\n| Region = [[CONCACAF]]\n| Region affiliation = \n| Headquarters = \n| President = \n| Website = {{URL|http://www.futsal.com |United States Futsal Federation}}\n}}\n\nThe '''United States Futsal Federation''' ('''USFF''') is one of the Futsal [[futsal in the United States|leagues in the United States]]. It is a body sanctioned by [[FIFA]] in the United States, and is a member of the [[United States Soccer Federation]].\n\nThe USFF was formed in 1981.  It was founded to promote the sport of [[futsal]] in the United States and to ensure that sport standards were followed.  According to the USFS's website, there are 110,000 members of the federation.<ref name=USFF>{{cite web|url=http://www.futsal.org/index.php/state-associations|title=UNITED STATES FUTSAL FEDERATION|publisher=United States Futsal Federation| accessdate=2009-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, the [[Boys and Girls Club of America]] adopted futsal, under USFF government, as an \"Olympic Focus Sport\", and began introducing it to the various clubs throughout the country.<ref name=USFF/> In that same, year, the [[American Youth Soccer Association]] became an associate member of the federation.\n\nThe USFF also works to introduce the sport to various [[YMCA]] chapters, the National High School Association of America, the [[NCAA]] and the National Junior College Association.\n\nThe federation sponsors sports clinics, national championships, and American teams in international competitions.\n\nThe federation is made up of individual state associations, which are responsible for promoting futsal at the local level. \n\nCureent coach of the United States national futsal team is Serbian [[Du\u0161an Jakica]]. <ref name=Futsal Feed>{{cite web|url=https://futsalfeed.com/original-content/the-us-head-coach-the-usa-could-become-one-of-the-best-futsal-nations-in-the-world|title=The US head coach: The USA could become one of the best futsal nations in the world|publisher=futsallfeed.com| accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==United States National Futsal Championship==\nThe first National Futsal Championship was held in [[Reno, Nevada]] in the mid-1980s. Since that time, several different levels of competition have been organized to hold annual championships. Championships are held in the Men's, Women, Under-19 Boys and Girls, the Under-16 Boys and Girls, and the Under-12 Boys and Girls Divisions. Originally, 8 teams per division were allowed to compete in each championship, but since 2004, 16 teams have participated in each competition.<ref name=USFF/>\n\nCurrently, there is still no National Futsal Championship in the United States and it is unknown when it will start<ref name=Futsal Feed>{{cite web|url=https://futsalfeed.com/original-content/the-us-head-coach-the-usa-could-become-one-of-the-best-futsal-nations-in-the-world|title=The US head coach: The USA could become one of the best futsal nations in the world|publisher=futsallfeed.com| accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.futsal.com U.S. Futsal official website]\n* [http://www.futsal.org/index.php/national-championship-results-1986-present List of US National Champions, from 1986 to present]\n{{USSoccer}}\n{{Futsal in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Futsal organizations]]\n[[Category:Futsal in the United States]]\n[[Category:Soccer governing bodies in the United States|Futsal]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football association\n| Logo = \n| Badge_size = 180px\n| Founded = \n| FIFA affiliation =\n| Region = [[CONCACAF]]\n| Region affiliation = \n| Headquarters = \n| President = \n| Website = {{URL|http://www.futsal.com |United States Futsal Federation}}\n}}\n\nThe '''United States Futsal Federation''' ('''USFF''') is one of the Futsal [[futsal in the United States|leagues in the United States]]. It is a body sanctioned by [[FIFA]] in the United States, and is a member of the [[United States Soccer Federation]].\n\nThe USFF was formed in 1981.  It was founded to promote the sport of [[futsal]] in the United States and to ensure that sport standards were followed.  According to the USFS's website, there are 110,000 members of the federation.<ref name=USFF>{{cite web|url=http://www.futsal.org/index.php/state-associations|title=UNITED STATES FUTSAL FEDERATION|publisher=United States Futsal Federation| accessdate=2009-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, the [[Boys and Girls Club of America]] adopted futsal, under USFF government, as an \"Olympic Focus Sport\", and began introducing it to the various clubs throughout the country.<ref name=USFF/> In that same, year, the [[American Youth Soccer Association]] became an associate member of the federation.\n\nThe USFF also works to introduce the sport to various [[YMCA]] chapters, the National High School Association of America, the [[NCAA]] and the National Junior College Association.\n\nThe federation sponsors sports clinics, national championships, and American teams in international competitions.\n\nThe federation is made up of individual state associations, which are responsible for promoting futsal at the local level.\n\n==United States National Futsal Championship==\nThe first National Futsal Championship was held in [[Reno, Nevada]] in the mid-1980s. Since that time, several different levels of competition have been organized to hold annual championships. Championships are held in the Men's, Women, Under-19 Boys and Girls, the Under-16 Boys and Girls, and the Under-12 Boys and Girls Divisions. Originally, 8 teams per division were allowed to compete in each championship, but since 2004, 16 teams have participated in each competition.<ref name=USFF/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.futsal.com U.S. Futsal official website]\n* [http://www.futsal.org/index.php/national-championship-results-1986-present List of US National Champions, from 1986 to present]\n{{USSoccer}}\n{{Futsal in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Futsal organizations]]\n[[Category:Futsal in the United States]]\n[[Category:Soccer governing bodies in the United States|Futsal]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Jerkovic9", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Futsal_Federation"}
{"title_page": "Charles Cauchon de Maupas", "text_new": "'''Charles Cauchon de Maupas et du Thour''' or '''de Tour''' (1566-1629), was a French ambassador to the Scottish and English court of [[James VI and I]].\n\nHe was the son of Jean-Baptiste Cauchon de Maupas and Marie de Morillon.\n\n==Scotland in 1602==\nEnglish and Scottish sources usually name him the \"Baron de Tour\" or \"Baron du Thour\". He was sent as ambassador to [[James VI of Scotland]] from [[Henry IV of France]]. He and his wife Anne de Gondi landed at Scarborough and travelled to Edinburgh through England, and met up with his ship at [[Leith]] on 21 July 1602.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1031.</ref> In August 1602 he met James VI in the garden of [[Falkland Palace]] and spoke with him for three quarters of an hour, often making him laugh. The Baron stayed in Falkland village for a few days while James went to Perth. When the king returned they hunting together in Falkland park and he met the queen [[Anne of Denmark]]. After this, he returned to his lodging in Leith, and the English diplomat George Nicholson spoke to him using [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar|Lord Sanquhar]] as an interpreter.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1033-4.</ref>\n\nAt [[Stirling Castle|Stirling]] he was feasted by the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] and had a discussion with his mother [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar]] at her house, [[Mar's Wark]]. He returned to Edinburgh, then went to [[Hamilton Palace|Hamilton]], hosted by [[John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton|Lord Hamilton]], hunting with the king and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]] and playing a card game called \"mawe\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1040.</ref>\n\n==England in 1617==\nIn 1617 [[Ben Jonson]] wrote a masque, ''[[Lovers Made Men]]'', to be presented by the [[James Hay, 1st Earl of Carlisle|Lord Hay]], to the Baron de Tour, at his house in London..\n\n==Family==\nCauchon married Anne de Gondi. Their son Henri Cauchon de Maupas (1604-1680) was bishop of Evreux.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cauchon, Charles}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:1566 births]]\n[[Category:1629 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Cauchon de Maupas et du Thour''' or '''de Tour''' (1566-1629), was a French ambassador to the Scottish and English court of [[James VI and I]].\n\nHe was the son of Jean-Baptiste Cauchon de Maupas and Marie de Morillon.\n\n==Scotland in 1602==\nEnglish and Scottish sources usually name him the \"Baron de Tour\" or \"Baron du Thour\". He was sent as ambassador to [[James VI of Scotland]] from [[Henry IV of France]]. He and his wife Anne de Gondi landed at Scarborough and travelled to Edinburgh through England, and met up with his ship at [[Leith]] on 21 July 1602.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1031.</ref> In August 1602 he met James VI in the garden of [[Falkland Palace]] and spoke with him for three quarters of an hour, often making him laugh. The Baron stayed in Falkland village for a few days while James went to Perth. When the king returned they hunting together in Falkland park and he met the queen [[Anne of Denmark]]. After this, he returned to his lodging in Leith, and the English diplomat George Nicholson spoke to him using [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar|Lord Sanquhar]] as an interpreter.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1033-4.</ref>\n\nAt [[Stirling Castle|Stirling]] he was feasted by the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] and had a discussion with his mother [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar]] at her house, [[Mar's Wark]]. He returned to Edinburgh, then went to [[Hamilton Palace|Hamilton]], hosted by [[John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton|Lord Hamilton]], hunting with the king and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]] and playing a card game called \"mawe\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1040.</ref>\n\n==England in 1617==\nIn 1617 [[Ben Jonson]] wrote a masque, ''[[Lovers made men]]'', to be presented by the [[James Hay, 1st Earl of Carlisle|Lord Hay]], to the Baron de Tour, at his house in London..\n\n==Family==\nCauchon married Anne de Gondi. Their son Henri Cauchon de Maupas (1604-1680) was bishop of Evreux.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cauchon, Charles}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:1566 births]]\n[[Category:1629 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEngland in 1617:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Cauchon_de_Maupas"}
{"title_page": "Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name        = [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Narrator\n| description = Outstanding Narrator in a Series or a Special\n| presenter   = [[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| year        = 2014 (awarded to [[Jeremy Irons]] for ''Game of Lions'')<ref>[https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2014/outstanding-narrator Outstanding Narrator Nominees/Winners 2014 Emmy Awards|Television Academy]</ref>\n| holder      = [[David Attenborough]], ''[[Our Planet]]'' ([[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019]])\n| website     = {{url|emmys.com}}\n}}\n\nIn 2014, the '''[[Primetime Emmy Award]]''' for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] was separated into two categories \u2013 '''Outstanding Narrator''' and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Character Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Character Voice-Over Performance]]. As with longform and reality, this split acknowledges and accommodates a general industry uptrend in the distinctly different achievements that are VO narration and VO character performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=EMMYS: TV Academy Splits Best Miniseries & TV Movie, Reality Program & Voice-Over Categories, Expands Combined Longform Fields To 6 Nominees, Sets Possibility For 7 Best Drama & Comedy Series Nominees|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/its-official-tv-academy-splits-best-miniseries-tv-movie-category/|accessdate=February 21, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Winners and nominations==\n===2010s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#bebebe\"\n! width=\"5%\" | Year\n! width=\"30%\" | Narrator\n! width=\"50%\" | Program\n! width=\"15%\" | Network\n|-\n|-\n| rowspan=6 style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2014 in television|2014]]<br /><small>[[66th Primetime Emmy Award